# tinyproxy.conf — Egress Proxy for Cowrie Malware Capture (Option B)
# Operator: copy this file before bringing up Module 2 with Option B active.
#
#   cp tinyproxy.conf.example ../../config/tinyproxy/tinyproxy.conf
#   sudo chown 100000:100000 ../../config/tinyproxy/tinyproxy.conf
#
# This file is bind-mounted read-only into the egress-proxy container at:
#   /etc/tinyproxy/tinyproxy.conf
#
# To change the allowlist or any setting: edit this file on the host and restart
# the egress-proxy container. No image rebuild is required.
#
# SECURITY MODEL (gatekeeper conditions 1-3, 7, 10):
#   - Only ports 80 and 443 are allowed via CONNECT (HTTP and HTTPS payloads).
#   - FTP/21 is EXCLUDED for the first 30 days (active-mode FTP creates a back-channel
#     data connection that bypasses the proxy and is a weaponization risk).
#     Re-evaluate after reviewing 30 days of Cowrie download URL logs.
#   - RFC1918 and 169.254.169.254 (DigitalOcean metadata) are blocked by nftables
#     egress rules on egress-net (Section 9 of honeypot-project-plans.md).
#   - DNS is pinned to 1.1.1.1/9.9.9.9 via the docker-compose.yml dns: directive.
#     This config file does NOT override DNS — that is handled at the container level.
#   - Logging goes to stderr (captured by Docker's log driver); no persistent log file
#     is written inside the container (compatible with read_only: true).

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# LISTEN ADDRESS AND PORT
# Tinyproxy listens on all interfaces within the container so that Cowrie
# (on honeypot-net, 172.20.0.0/24) can reach it at http://egress-proxy:8888.
# The proxy is NOT exposed to the host — no ports: directive in docker-compose.yml.
Port 8888
Listen 0.0.0.0

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ACCESS CONTROL
# Allow requests from any source IP within the container network.
# The effective scope is honeypot-net (172.20.0.0/24) only because no other
# network can reach this container. This Allow line covers Cowrie's IP within
# that subnet without hard-coding it (IP assignment is dynamic per compose run).
Allow 0.0.0.0/0

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# CONNECT PORT ALLOWLIST (gatekeeper condition 2)
# ONLY ports 80 (HTTP) and 443 (HTTPS) are permitted.
# Any attacker-supplied URL targeting other ports (FTP:21, SMTP:25, arbitrary C2 ports)
# will be rejected by tinyproxy with a 403 before it reaches egress-net.
# DO NOT add port 21 — active-mode FTP opens a back-channel data connection
# that bypasses the proxy and may expose the VPS IP to attacker-controlled servers.
# Re-evaluate FTP after 30 days of observed Cowrie download URL patterns.
ConnectPort 80
ConnectPort 443

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# FILTER / URL ALLOWLIST
# FilterDefaultDeny is intentionally set to No (deny-list mode, not allow-list mode).
# Reason: URL-pattern allow-listing is brittle and maintenance-intensive; the nftables
# egress rules (Section 9) and the ConnectPort ceiling above are the primary controls.
# If a future operator wants URL-level filtering, uncomment Filter and FilterDefaultDeny
# and provide a Filter file path — but this requires the filter file to be bind-mounted
# into the container and is incompatible with the current read_only: true posture
# unless the filter file is in a read-only bind-mount.
#
# Filter /etc/tinyproxy/filter       # uncomment only if a filter file is mounted
# FilterDefaultDeny No

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# LOGGING
# Log to stderr so Docker captures all tinyproxy output via its log driver.
# Compatible with read_only: true (no file write needed).
# The /var/log/tinyproxy tmpfs in docker-compose.yml provides a writable target
# if tinyproxy requires a log directory to exist — it does not receive file writes here.
LogFile ""
LogLevel Info

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# UPSTREAM PROXY
# No upstream proxy — tinyproxy connects directly to the internet via egress-net.
# Upstream /

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# TIMEOUT
# Disconnect stalled connections after 90 seconds.
# Prevents a single attacker-supplied slow payload from holding a proxy thread open.
Timeout 90

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# MAXIMUM CLIENTS
# Limit concurrent proxy sessions. At 15 max Cowrie sessions and one download per session,
# 20 is a generous ceiling that prevents proxy thread exhaustion.
MaxClients 20

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# VIA HEADER
# Suppress the Via header to avoid leaking proxy presence to the attacker's server.
# An attacker whose C2 server logs HTTP headers would see the Via header and know the
# download was intercepted/proxied — this would be a honeypot fingerprint tell.
DisableViaHeader Yes

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ANONYMOUS MODE — INTENTIONALLY NOT SET
#
# WARNING: tinyproxy's "Anonymous" directive works as an ALLOWLIST of headers to KEEP,
# not a blocklist of headers to strip. Listing "Anonymous X-Forwarded-For" tells tinyproxy
# to strip everything EXCEPT X-Forwarded-For — the exact opposite of what you want.
#
# Correct posture: do NOT set any Anonymous directives. Instead:
#   - "DisableViaHeader Yes" above suppresses the Via header entirely.
#   - Tinyproxy does NOT add X-Forwarded-For by default (only added if XTinyproxy Yes).
#   - XTinyproxy is not set, so no X-Tinyproxy header is added.
# Result: the proxy adds no identifying headers to forwarded requests, which is the
# desired behaviour. Adding Anonymous directives here would BREAK this by enabling
# anonymous mode and preserving only the explicitly listed headers (breaking cookies,
# Authorization, Content-Type, etc. for attacker download URLs).
#
# If you later need to explicitly strip a specific header, use:
#   Header "X-Header-Name" ""
# instead of the Anonymous directive.

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# USER / GROUP — INTENTIONALLY NOT SET
#
# WARNING: Setting "User nobody" / "Group nogroup" here conflicts with the Docker-level
# containment. The compose service sets:
#   user: "100000:100000"
#   cap_drop: [ALL]   (drops CAP_SETUID and CAP_SETGID)
# With all capabilities dropped, tinyproxy's setuid("nobody") call fails with EPERM.
# Depending on the tinyproxy version, this either crashes the container (blocking Cowrie
# via depends_on: service_healthy) or silently ignores the directive and runs as UID 100000.
#
# The correct approach: privilege drop is handled entirely at the Docker layer. The
# compose "user: 100000:100000" directive is the authoritative UID/GID control.
# Do not set User or Group in this file — tinyproxy will run as the UID Docker assigned
# without attempting any setuid call.
